Contraband Slaves Not Returned to Owners!
Confederate Support Increases in the South!

513
The Union Passes Confiscation Act.
\tThe U.S. government has decided, that as the South is in rebellion against the Union, the protection of their property is no longer required. From this day on, according to this Act, Union armies are allowed to confiscate southern property that is needed for the Union war effort.\n\tAlso, captured slaves are considered contraband and will no longer be required to be returned to their owners. Supplying armies in enemy territory is made easier and former slaves flock to find safety with the Union armies. The contraband slaves are sometimes allowed to remain with the army for manual labor, thus freeing up troops for more important tasks.\n\tThe news has been received with a great uproar in the Confederacy. Union armies are considered to be conducting criminal acts on behalf of their government, yet more proof of northern aggression.
