The Union Passes Militia Act II.
\tThe Union calls for more volunteers to serve; the contracts are for one year at a time. The states are given new recruitment quotas and recruitment officers around the nation are working tirelessly to muster new regiments to be added to Lincoln's armies.\n\tThe three months of service that was required from the initially called 75,000 men has turned out to be too short a time to drill effective fighting soldiers for the Union. Further training in marching, discipline and basic soldiering was required.\n\tAs more volunteers are required, the U.S. Congress keeps sanctioning the acts and authorizing additional volunteers to be called to arms. So far, there have been more volunteers ready for service than the states could handle, but it's likely the longer contracts and service required will restrain the fervor in the long run.
