\tThe Union calls for more volunteers to serve; the contracts are for two years at a time. The states are given new recruitment quotas and recruitment officers around the nation are working tirelessly to muster new regiments to be added to Lincoln's armies.\n\tThe need for new volunteers is clearly felt in the armies where the raw regiments are added. While usually regiments muster at or near full their strength of 1,000 soldiers, when reaching the front lines hundreds of these have already succumbed to sickness or deserted from the ranks. The regiments in the field are much smaller in size, averaging only half of their full strength when engaging in combat with the enemy.\n\tSome field commanders feel the current recruitment system is not optimal, as existing regiments are not filled with new volunteers when their numbers go down, instead the states keep forming new regiments to fill the given quotas.
