503
The Union Passes Enrollment Act I.
\tThe U.S. Congress has passed an Enrollment Act, or Draft Act, to provide fresh manpower for the Union Army. The Act is the first genuine national conscription law. The law requires the enrollment of every male citizen and those immigrants who have filed for citizenship, aged between 20 and 45 years of age, unless exempted by the Act.\n\tThe Provost Marshal General is recreated to administer the national implementation of the Enrollment Act. James Barnet Fry is appointed to the position and answers directly to the Secretary of War. Beneath Fry are the State Acting Assistant Provost Marshal Generals.\n\tDrafted citizens may opt out of service by either furnishing a suitable substitute to take their place or paying 300 dollars. Due to this practice the general public has already started talking in terms of "rich man's war, poor man's fight."\n\tIf this enrollment is implemented to raise new draft regiments, it's almost certain that the government will suffer a loss of support in the recruiting state and there is a possibility of riots breaking out.
