The Union Passes Enrolment Act II.
\tThe United States Congress has passed further amendments to the most hated policy of the war so far, Enrollment. The government is now forcing all eligible men to serve under pain of penalty, if not exempted by the Enrollment Act. If a drafted person tries to avoid military service he could lose his citizenship!\n\tThe commutation fee of 300 dollars has been limited to be effective for only one year. After this time the draftee will be required to serve or to find a substitute for themselves.\n\tThe general public has been opposing the draft, it's seen as a way of extorting money from wealthy citizens to pay for the poorly led war effort. For the poor there has not been much choice but to serve. The drafted soldiers have generally been very reluctant to follow orders. Desertion soars once the bullets start flying and the morale in the armies has been plummeting since draftees started filling the ranks.
