519
Union Blockade of the Southern Ports.
\tThe European superpowers agree that a blockade is a legal form of warfare. As only the mightiest navies in the world are able to fully blockade an adversary, the agreement has been in place to ensure that third parties would be discouraged from taking part in any conflict, as retaliation would follow.\n\tToday the tables are turned, the U.S. government declares its blockade of the southern ports to have legal status and warns that all foreign trade fleets should abstain from attempting to trade with the blockaded Confederate ports. This declaration has a threat written between the lines, as any attempt to carry on trading with the South would be liable to retaliation.\n\tIn Europe the declaration has been viewed as a direct challenge to their authority and relations with the United States are cooling down, with trade treaties being cancelled. New ways of running the blockade are planned and more safe havens for the Confederate blockade runners to use as bases of operations are sought. As long as the Union blockade proves to be effective, it's likely that the Europeans will be forced to remain neutral, as any violation of the blockade would undermine their own operations elsewhere in the world. 
