In March 1857 John B. Floyd became the Secretary of War, while in office he undertook efforts to bolster arsenals in the Southern states by transferring weapons from northern armories. However his actions were revealed and he was forced to resign in December 1860. After this, military officials increased security measures, slowing the movement of weapons to the South, and weapon stockpiles in the South are reduced. The abrupt crackdown also shocks the southern population, making some think twice about openly promoting secession.
