Following the Pacific Railroad Surveys of 1853-1855, northern politicians secure the funding to build a transcontinental railroad, from Council Bluffs, Iowa, all the way to Sacramento, California. By 1861 the work is finished in Utah and the railway greatly increases trade with California. With the increased prosperity, the United States credit rating, along with investment in railroads, is soaring, helped by experienced railroad construction laborers, mainly Chinese and Irish immigrants.
