528
A.C.S.A. Units are Formed.
\tOn March 6, 1861, an Act was passed to form a Regular Army organization for the Confederate States of America. The Army of the Confederate States of America, A.C.S.A., is the Regular Army and is authorized to include 15,015 men, including 744 officers.\n\tAt first it looked unlikely that such an organization could be properly formed and trained. However, with the Regular Act recruitment is at full speed. The nucleus of the new C.S. Regulars are southern West Point graduates and former U.S. Regulars who have remained loyal to their home states after secession. More Regulars are recruited from among the veterans of the Indian Wars, the filibustering expeditions, and the fighting in Kansas. These troops are given the best equipment and they are drilled hard, compared to the volunteers and militia in service of the states or the Provisional Army.\n\tWhile this order creates a small number of well-trained units with combat experience, the Provisional Army will lose many experienced men, and the military experience of the Confederate armies will decline as a whole.
