In May 1854 the Kansas-Nebraska Act created new territories. Neighboring slave states organize parties of "Border Ruffians" to intimidate the so-called Free-Staters. In 1856 this escalated into bitter fighting, known as "Bleeding Kansas." In October 1859 the fourth and final draft of the state constitution allows slavery in Kansas, a statute that stands when the Territory becomes a State in 1861. This victory for the institution of slavery greatly inspires the southern population.
