After the 1853-1855 Pacific Railroad Surveys, Southern politicians secure funding to build a transcontinental railroad from Houston, Texas, to Los Angeles in California. By 1861 the work is finished. The rail line greatly increases trade with California, allowing Southern control over the southernmost trade routes. With the increased prosperity, the Confederate credit rating and investment in railroads are both soaring, helped by the experienced railroad construction laborers, mainly Chinese and Irish immigrants.
